{
    "chapters": [
        {
            "id": 1,
            "name_pali": "Yamaka Vagga",
            "name_en": "The Pairs",
            "summary": "This chapter explores the fundamental duality of mental states and their consequences. It emphasizes how our thoughts shape our reality and determine our happiness or suffering.",
            "verses": [
                {
                    "id": 1,
                    "verse_number": 1,
                    "pali": "Manopubbaṅgamā dhammā, manoseṭṭhā manomayā; Manasā ce paduṭṭhena, bhāsati vā karoti vā; Tato naṃ dukkhamanveti, cakkaṃva vahato padaṃ.",
                    "translation": "Mind precedes all mental states. Mind is their chief; they are all mind-wrought. If with an impure mind a person speaks or acts, suffering follows him like the wheel that follows the foot of the ox.",
                    "commentary": "This verse teaches that all our experiences originate from the mind. When we act or speak with a corrupted mind filled with greed, hatred, or delusion, suffering inevitably follows us. Just as a wheel follows the ox that pulls the cart, our suffering is inseparable from our unwholesome mental states.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Cakkhupala Thera",
                        "content": "Cakkhupala was a monk who became blind while meditating. In a past life, he had been a physician who deliberately blinded a woman to keep her dependent on him. The Buddha explained that his blindness was the result of that past evil deed. Despite his blindness, Cakkhupala attained Arahantship through diligent practice. One night, while walking in meditation, he accidentally stepped on some insects. Other monks accused him of killing intentionally, but the Buddha declared him innocent, explaining that an Arahant cannot intentionally kill, as his mind is pure. This story illustrates how past unwholesome actions (done with an impure mind) bring suffering, while present pure actions lead to liberation."
                    }
                },
                {
                    "id": 2,
                    "verse_number": 2,
                    "pali": "Manopubbaṅgamā dhammā, manoseṭṭhā manomayā; Manasā ce pasannena, bhāsati vā karoti vā; Tato naṃ sukhamanveti, chāyāva anapāyinī.",
                    "translation": "Mind precedes all mental states. Mind is their chief; they are all mind-wrought. If with a pure mind a person speaks or acts, happiness follows him like his never-departing shadow.",
                    "commentary": "This is the positive counterpart to the first verse. When our mind is pure, filled with loving-kindness, compassion, and wisdom, happiness naturally follows all our actions. Like a shadow that never leaves us, this happiness is inseparable from wholesome mental states.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Matthakundali",
                        "content": "Matthakundali was a young boy from a wealthy family whose miserly father never gave him proper food or clothing. When the boy fell ill and was dying, his father finally called a physician, but it was too late. The Buddha visited the dying boy and helped him develop a pure, serene mind by guiding him to offer a simple mental gift. With this pure intention, the boy died peacefully and was reborn in a heavenly realm. The Buddha then revealed that in a past life, Matthakundali had been a generous person, and this past wholesome karma, combined with his final pure thought, brought him happiness. This demonstrates how a pure mind, even in the last moments, can lead to a fortunate rebirth."
                    }
                },
                {
                    "id": 3,
                    "verse_number": 3,
                    "pali": "Akkocchi maṃ avadhi maṃ, ajini maṃ ahāsi me; Ye ca taṃ upanayhanti, veraṃ tesaṃ na sammati.",
                    "translation": "He abused me, he struck me, he overpowered me, he robbed me. Those who harbor such thoughts do not still their hatred.",
                    "commentary": "This verse addresses the destructive nature of holding grudges. When we constantly replay past wrongs in our minds and nurse our grievances, we keep our hatred alive. The mind that clings to resentment cannot find peace. The verse teaches that it is not the original wrong that perpetuates our suffering, but our own mental habit of dwelling on it.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Thera Tissa",
                        "content": "Two monks, both named Tissa, lived in Savatthi. One day, the junior Tissa accidentally stepped on the senior Tissa's robe, tearing it. The senior monk became furious and held a grudge, constantly thinking 'He tore my robe, he disrespected me.' His mind became so consumed with anger that he couldn't meditate or find peace. When the Buddha learned of this, he spoke this verse, explaining that the junior monk's action was accidental and minor, but the senior monk's continuous dwelling on it was causing his own suffering. The Buddha taught that by letting go of the grudge, the senior monk could immediately find peace. Upon hearing this teaching, the senior Tissa released his resentment and soon attained Arahantship."
                    }
                },
                {
                    "id": 4,
                    "verse_number": 4,
                    "pali": "Akkocchi maṃ avadhi maṃ, ajini maṃ ahāsi me; Ye ca taṃ nupanayhanti, veraṃ tesūpasammati.",
                    "translation": "He abused me, he struck me, he overpowered me, he robbed me. Those who do not harbor such thoughts still their hatred.",
                    "commentary": "This verse presents the solution to the problem described in verse 3. By choosing not to dwell on past wrongs, by not rehearsing our grievances, we allow our hatred to naturally subside. Peace comes not from getting revenge or receiving apologies, but from our own decision to release resentment from our minds.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of the Quarreling Monks",
                        "content": "In the city of Kosambi, monks became divided into two factions over a minor disciplinary matter. Each group believed they were right and held grudges against the other. The dispute escalated until the monastery became unbearable. The Buddha tried to reconcile them, but they were too attached to their positions. Eventually, the Buddha left them and spent the rainy season alone in the forest with an elephant. The lay supporters, disappointed by the monks' behavior, stopped offering them alms. Facing hunger and shame, the monks finally realized their foolishness. They came to the Buddha, confessed their fault, and genuinely let go of their grudges. The Buddha then taught them this verse, explaining that their suffering came not from the original disagreement, but from their refusal to let it go. Once they truly abandoned their resentment, harmony was immediately restored."
                    }
                },
                {
                    "id": 5,
                    "verse_number": 5,
                    "pali": "Na hi verena verāni, sammantīdha kudācanaṃ; Averena ca sammanti, esa dhammo sanantano.",
                    "translation": "Hatred is never appeased by hatred in this world. By non-hatred alone is hatred appeased. This is an eternal law.",
                    "commentary": "This verse expresses one of the Buddha's most profound teachings on conflict resolution. Responding to hatred with more hatred only perpetuates the cycle of suffering. Only by meeting hatred with loving-kindness, understanding, and forgiveness can we truly end conflict. This is described as an eternal law (sanantano dhammo) because it is a universal truth that transcends time and culture.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Prince Dighavu",
                        "content": "Long ago, King Brahmadatta of Kasi conquered the kingdom of Kosala and killed King Dighiti. Before his death, King Dighiti whispered to his son, Prince Dighavu, 'Do not look long, do not look short' - meaning 'Do not perpetuate hatred, but also do not forget the Dhamma.' Prince Dighavu escaped and later became a servant in King Brahmadatta's palace, eventually becoming the king's favorite attendant. One day, while alone with the king in the forest, Dighavu had the perfect opportunity for revenge. He drew his sword, but remembered his father's words. Instead of killing the king, he revealed his identity and explained the teaching of non-hatred. King Brahmadatta was so moved by this act of mercy and wisdom that he returned the kingdom to Dighavu and the two kingdoms lived in peace. The Buddha used this story to illustrate that only non-hatred can truly end hatred."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "name_pali": "Appamāda Vagga",
            "name_en": "Heedfulness",
            "summary": "This chapter emphasizes the importance of mindfulness and diligence in spiritual practice. Heedfulness is presented as the path to the deathless, while heedlessness leads to death.",
            "verses": [
                {
                    "id": 6,
                    "verse_number": 21,
                    "pali": "Appamādo amatapadaṃ, pamādo maccuno padaṃ; Appamattā na mīyanti, ye pamattā yathā matā.",
                    "translation": "Heedfulness is the path to the Deathless. Heedlessness is the path to death. The heedful die not. The heedless are as if dead already.",
                    "commentary": "This verse establishes the fundamental importance of mindfulness (appamāda) in Buddhist practice. The 'Deathless' refers to Nibbana, the unconditioned state beyond birth and death. Those who are heedful, constantly aware and mindful, progress toward liberation. Those who are heedless, living in distraction and delusion, are spiritually dead even while physically alive.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Samavati",
                        "content": "Queen Samavati was known for her exceptional mindfulness and loving-kindness. Despite being the target of a jealous co-wife's plots, she maintained constant awareness and never responded with anger. When her rival set fire to her quarters, Samavati and her attendants died while meditating on loving-kindness. The Buddha explained that because of their heedfulness and pure minds at the moment of death, they were all reborn in heavenly realms. Their physical death was not truly death, as they had cultivated the path to the Deathless through constant mindfulness."
                    }
                },
                {
                    "id": 7,
                    "verse_number": 22,
                    "pali": "Etaṃ visesato ñatvā, appamādamhi paṇḍitā; Appamāde pamodanti, ariyānaṃ gocare ratā.",
                    "translation": "Clearly understanding this excellence of heedfulness, the wise exult therein and enjoy the resort of the Noble Ones.",
                    "commentary": "The wise recognize that heedfulness is not a burden but a source of joy. They delight in mindfulness because they understand it leads to liberation. The 'resort of the Noble Ones' refers to the meditative states and wisdom that arise from sustained mindfulness practice.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Mahakassapa Thera",
                        "content": "Venerable Mahakassapa was renowned for his strict adherence to the ascetic practices and constant mindfulness. Even in old age, he never relaxed his vigilance. When other monks suggested he should take it easy, he replied that the joy he found in heedfulness far exceeded any comfort from relaxation. The Buddha praised him, saying that Mahakassapa's delight in mindfulness was the mark of a true Noble One. His constant awareness led him to become one of the Buddha's foremost disciples and the leader of the First Buddhist Council."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "name_pali": "Citta Vagga",
            "name_en": "The Mind",
            "summary": "This chapter focuses on the nature of the mind and the importance of training it. The mind is compared to various things to illustrate its restless and difficult-to-control nature.",
            "verses": [
                {
                    "id": 8,
                    "verse_number": 33,
                    "pali": "Phandanaṃ capalaṃ cittaṃ, dūrakkhaṃ dunnivārayaṃ; Ujuṃ karoti medhāvī, usukāro va tejanaṃ.",
                    "translation": "The flickering, fickle mind, difficult to guard, difficult to control—the wise one straightens it as a fletcher straightens an arrow.",
                    "commentary": "This verse uses the simile of an arrow-maker to illustrate the work of mental training. Just as a fletcher must carefully straighten a crooked arrow shaft, the wise person must patiently work to straighten the wandering mind. The mind's natural tendency is to flicker from object to object, making it difficult to control, but through persistent effort, it can be trained.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Meghiya Thera",
                        "content": "Meghiya was the Buddha's attendant who, seeing a beautiful mango grove, asked permission to meditate there alone. Despite the Buddha's advice to wait, Meghiya insisted. In the grove, his mind was assailed by unwholesome thoughts and he couldn't concentrate. Frustrated, he returned to the Buddha, who taught him this verse. The Buddha explained that the mind is like a wild animal that must be gradually tamed, not forced. He taught Meghiya five methods to steady the mind: good friendship, moral conduct, wise conversation, energy, and wisdom. Following this guidance, Meghiya eventually attained Arahantship."
                    }
                },
                {
                    "id": 9,
                    "verse_number": 34,
                    "pali": "Vārijova thale khitto, okamokata ubbhato; Pariphandatidaṃ cittaṃ, māradheyyaṃ pahātave.",
                    "translation": "Like a fish out of water, thrown on dry ground, this mind thrashes about, trying to escape Mara's command.",
                    "commentary": "This verse compares the untrained mind to a fish struggling on dry land. When we try to remove the mind from its habitual patterns of craving and aversion (Mara's domain), it resists violently. The image conveys both the difficulty of mental training and the urgency of the task—just as a fish will die if left on land, we suffer when caught in Mara's realm.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Cittahattha",
                        "content": "Cittahattha was a wealthy householder who practiced meditation but struggled with a restless mind. Whenever he sat to meditate, his mind would race with thoughts of his business, family, and possessions. He felt like he was drowning in mental chaos. The Buddha taught him this verse and explained that the mind's resistance is natural—it has been conditioned by lifetimes of craving. The Buddha advised him to be patient and persistent, comparing the process to training a wild elephant. With continued practice, Cittahattha's mind gradually settled, and he eventually attained the first stage of enlightenment."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
