        {
            "id": 5,
            "name_pali": "Bāla Vagga",
            "name_en": "The Fool",
            "summary": "This chapter describes the characteristics of the fool and the consequences of foolish behavior. It contrasts the fool with the wise person and emphasizes the suffering that comes from ignorance.",
            "verses": [
                {
                    "id": 12,
                    "verse_number": 60,
                    "pali": "Dīghā jāgarato ratti, dīghaṃ santassa yojanaṃ; Dīgho bālānaṃ saṃsāro, saddhammaṃ avijānataṃ.",
                    "translation": "Long is the night to the wakeful; long is the league to the weary; long is samsara to the foolish who know not the true Dhamma.",
                    "commentary": "This verse uses three similes to illustrate how suffering is prolonged by ignorance. Just as night seems endless to one who cannot sleep, and a journey seems interminable to one who is exhausted, the cycle of rebirth (samsara) seems endless to those who do not understand the Buddha's teachings. Knowledge of the true Dhamma provides the way out of this suffering.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Kisagotami",
                        "content": "Kisagotami's young son died, and in her grief, she refused to accept his death. Carrying the child's body, she went from house to house asking for medicine to revive him. People thought she had gone mad. Finally, someone directed her to the Buddha. The Buddha told her he could help, but first she must bring a mustard seed from a house where no one had ever died. Kisagotami went from house to house, but everywhere she heard stories of death—parents, children, spouses, friends. Gradually, she realized that death is universal. She understood that her suffering was prolonged by her refusal to accept this truth. She cremated her son's body and returned to the Buddha, who taught her this verse. Understanding the true Dhamma, she was no longer a fool lost in samsara, and she eventually attained Arahantship."
                    }
                },
                {
                    "id": 13,
                    "verse_number": 61,
                    "pali": "Carañce nādhigaccheyya, seyyaṃ sadisamattano; Ekacariyaṃ daḷhaṃ kayirā, natthi bāle sahāyatā.",
                    "translation": "If one cannot find a companion who is better or equal, let one resolutely pursue a solitary course; there is no fellowship with the foolish.",
                    "commentary": "This verse advises that it is better to walk the spiritual path alone than in the company of fools. Foolish companions can lead us astray, reinforcing unwholesome habits and wrong views. If we cannot find wise companions, solitude is preferable, as it allows us to focus on our practice without negative influences.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of a Monk and His Former Wife",
                        "content": "A monk was practicing meditation in the forest when his former wife, who had not accepted his ordination, came to tempt him to return to lay life. She used various seductive means to lure him back. The monk, remembering this verse taught by the Buddha, realized that association with her would be association with a fool who did not understand the Dhamma. He resolutely refused her advances and continued his solitary practice. His determination was so strong that he soon attained Arahantship. The Buddha later praised him, saying that solitude with wisdom is far superior to companionship with those who would lead us away from the path."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
