                {
                    "id": 14,
                    "verse_number": 76,
                    "pali": "Nidhīnaṃva pavattāraṃ, yaṃ passe vajjadassinaṃ; Niggayhavādiṃ medhāviṃ, tādisaṃ paṇḍitaṃ bhaje; Tādisaṃ bhajamānassa, seyyo hoti na pāpiyo.",
                    "translation": "One should follow a wise person who points out one's faults as if pointing out hidden treasure. It is always better, never worse, to associate with such a wise person.",
                    "commentary": "This verse teaches the value of constructive criticism from a wise person. Just as we would be grateful to someone who shows us hidden treasure, we should appreciate those who point out our faults, as this helps us improve. The wise person who corrects us is a true friend, and associating with such people always leads to our betterment.",
                    "story": {
                        "title": "The Story of Radha",
